{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_pakula_ver02/data/sn84026749/00222254401/1927032301/0067.xml":{"full_text":"Fine Playing Marks\nRadio Bridge\nt- East met West last night in the radio bridge game broadcast\nfrom Station WRG, in which two Californians, Mrs. Helen M.\nHtibbard. of San Francisco, and Mrs. Catherine A. Streeter, of\nLbs Angeles, participated as partners of Mr. Work and Mr.\nWhitehead, respectively.\nMrs. Hubbard was Dealer, in the*\n\u2022South\u201d position. She held: Spades.\nA, 5. 1; Hearts. Q. io, 9. 3. 2; Dia\nmonds. 71 Clubs. A.Q. 9. 6\nMr. Whitehead, \"West.\u201d held:\nSpades, K.- J, 7.6; Hearts. K.\n4; Diamonds, Q, J, 10; Clubs K, J.\nMr. Work, \u2018.'North,\u201d held: Spadbs,\n-4; Hearts. A, J, 8. S; Diamonds,\nK\u00bb 6, Clubs, 7,4, 4. 3.\nX .'Mrs. Streeter, \u201cBast.\" held:\nSpades 10, 8. 2; Hearts, 7,5; Dia\nmonds, A, 9, 8. 6,4, 3; Clubs, 8, 2.\nMrs. Hubbard identified herself\nwith the modern school ot bidding\nby opening with, one heart. This\ndeclaration was in direct opposition\nto the former theory that quteen\nhigh suits never should be bid\ninitially, or, if bid, that they should\nbe a ear-marked by calling two in\nstead of one.\nThere are many hands, of the\ntype-of that held by Mrs. Hubbard,\nwhich are entirely too strong to\npass, and with which the queen\nhigh suit Is distinctly the best de\nclaration. When the old theory,\nthat such hands should be passed\non the first round, -and bld second\narily if at all. is adhered to, it\nfrequently results in the passing\nout of a hand, which, if bld by\ndealer, would have produced a game\nfor his side.\nFurthermore, to follow the theory\nthat with such hands a bid of two\nshould be made in order to show\nthat the suit named does not con\ntain an ace or king, also results\nmoat unsatisfactorily. This two\nbi<|, once generally conventional,\nhas now been abandoned. As Mr.\nWork expressed it, it is obviously\nfooHsh to contend-that a hand not\nstrong enough for a bld of one\nshould be opened with fwo.\nTwo Quick Tricks\nIn making her bid of one heart;\nMrs, Hubbard followed the modern\nconvention which sanctions the\noriginal bid of a five-card suit headed\nby king and one other honor, or\nqueen and one other honor, provided\nthe hand contains two quick tricks\non the side. These two quick tricks\nmay bo either two aces (as in this\ninstance), one ace and one king\nqueen, or two king-queens. Mrs.\nHubbard preferred the heart to a\nno-trump because of the singleton\ndiamond. She also preferred the\nmijjor bid to a club declaration,\nwhich also would have been sound.\nfMr. Whitehead, the next bidder,\nsaid one spade. He showed good\njudgment in bidding .instead of\ndoubling informatorily, a.s some\nwould have done. The spade decla\nration gave him a chance to show\nthe character of his hand with a low\nbid; being a following bid. it did not\nnecessarily announce two quick\ntricks. Had he doubled, he probably\nwould have received a minor answer\nfrom Mrs. Streeter, over which he\nwould have had tcfttd two, spades.\nMr. Work, \u201cNorth,\": with good\nassistance for his partner's heart\nsuit, said two hearts.\n\u201cEast\u201d Passes\nMrs. Streeter passed. Although she\nhad normal support for Mr. White\nhead\u2019s spades, she did not have suf\nficient high card strength to justify\na raise, nor was her hand strong\nenough for three diamonds.\nThe others passed, making Mrs.\nHubbard declarer with her contract\ntwo hearts.\nMy. Whitehead left the queen of\nRENTS REDUCED\nDOWNTOWN\nAPARTMENTS\n1321MSLN.W.\nJust East Thomas Circle\nOne room, kitchen and UM ft\nbath, only\nTwo rooms, kitchenette (P EA\nand bath, only\nElevator Service\nEasy Walk to Business\nSection and Departments\nH. R. HOWENSTEIN CO.\n1311 H ST. N. W.\nwiring/\nFIXTURES\nAND BULB 3\nFor a\nSix-Room House\n\u2022150\nTimo faymente Arransed\nt MUDDIMANI\nns ISU, NA i\u00ab\ng AUANTIpCITY\nJ SMQAL witffEtMnS 1\na I\na \u26664a*\u00bb\u00bb6a*awSeKhp\u00abSi 1\nSiofl* and tatty ratMqnfwmfft B\nwritefyrniitHMMir, .g-\nSTTTZERHOTELCa g\ni diamonds, inasmuch as he did not\nwant to lead away from his minor\ntenace in spades o: clubs, or from\nh.s king and one heart.\nAs soon as Dummy was down\nthe Declarer, Mrs. Hubbard, reck\noned the game-going possibilities of\nthe combined hands. Seeing Dum\nmy\u2019s queen of spades and the ace\nin her own hand she knew at once\nwhy Mr. Whitehead did not lead\nspades. Figuring that he held the\nking-jack,- Mrs. Hubbard saw she\ncould make two spade tricks. She\nwas liable to lose a heart trick to\nthe king if held by Mrs. Streeter.\nShe also stood to lose one diamond\ntrick and two or three club tricks,\ndepending on the location of the\nking-jack-ten of the latter suit.\nAce la Known\nBy Mr. Whitehead\u2019s lead of the\nqueen of diamonds the ace was\nmarked in Mrs. Streeter\u2019s hand, as\nMrs. Hubbard was certain that Mr.\nWhitehead would not lead the queen\nIf he held the ace. Therefore, since\nthere was no question as to whether\nDummy should cover the 2 of dia\nmonds, Mrs. Streeter played the 8\nas an invitation to Mr. Whitehead\nto continue the suit; and Declarer\nplayed her singleton 7.\nMr. Whitehead continued with the\njack of diamonds; Dummy played\nthe 5; Mrs. Streeter completed her\nsignal by playing the 3 of diamonds;\nand Declarer trumped with the 2 of\nhearts.\nMrs. Hubbard led the 3 of hearts.\nShe knew she could catch the king\nif it were held by Mr. Whitehead,\n\"West;\u2019\u2019 but that if it were guarded\nin Mrs. Streeter\u2019s hand, it was\nbound to win. She had everything\nto gain by taking the finesse.\nMr. Whitehead could see it made\nno difference whether he went up\nwith his king at once or played the\n4. With the king in his own hand\nand the ace-jack in Dummy, he\nknew that Declarer must hold, the\nqueen to five hearts, and probably\nthe 10 also. Therefore he could\nnot benefit his part\u2019w whichever\nway he played the hearts. He played\nthe 4; Dummy finessed the 8 spot,\nas the only higher adverse heart\nwas the king; and Mrs. Streeter\nplayed the S.\nDummy led the kins of diamonds:\nMrs. Streeter played the ace; Dec\nlarer trumped with the 9 of hearts;\nMr. Whitehead played the 10 of\ndiamonds.\nMrs. Hubbard continued with the\n10 of hearts: Mr. Whitehead played\nhis .king; Dummy the ace; Mrs.\nStreeter the 7,\nMrs Hubbard now planned to\nthrow the lead to Mr. Whitehead,\nto force him, if possible, to lead\nspades from his king-jack,, or e\u2019se\na club up to her tenace in clubs.\nTherefore, Declarer led the 3 ot\nclubs from Dummy; Mrs. Streeter\nplayed the 8; and Declarer finessed\nthe 9. She expected to lose either\nthe 10 or the jack, but wanted to\ndo so in order to put Mr. White\nhead. in the lead Mr. Whitehead\nplayed the 10. .t.-5..;\nMr. Whitehead was now in a\nquandary for a lead. He could\nplace Declarer with the ace of\nrpades and the ace and probably\nalso the queen of clubs. Inasmuch\nas the the passing of the previous\nclub trick to him evidently was a\nshrewd move on the part of Mrs.\nHubbard to force him tp lead.-either\na spade or a club. It made little\nuifference to Mr. Whitehead which\nof these two suits he led. If he led\na spade, he would not make a spade\ntrick, but he would make another\nclub; if he led a club, he- would not\nmake another club trick, but would\nmake a spade.\nLeads Ace of Clubs\nHowever, the club would throw\nthe lead into Declarer\u2019s own hand,\nso Mr. Whitehead led the jack of\nclubs: Dummy played the 4;. Mrs.\nStreeter the 2; Mrs. Hubbard the\nqueen.\nMrs. Hubbard led the ace of\nclubs; Mr. Whitehead played the\nking; Dummy the 5; Mrs. Streeter\ndiscarded the 4 of diamonds; Mrs.\nHubbard continued with the 6 of\nclubs; Mr. Whitehead discarded the\n6 of spades; Dummy played the 7\nof clubs; Mrs. Streeter discarded the\n2 of spades.\nAt this point Mrs. Hubbard con\nceded the king of spades and claimed\nthe other three tricks winning\ngame, with 40 for four h< ors\ndivided, s\nMrs. Hubbard played a winning\ngame from the outset, when she\nsaw the necessity of preparing the\nground for an end play by strip\nping the Dummy hand of diamonds\nand Mr. Whitehead\u2019s hand of\ntrumps, so that by throwing My.\nWhitehead into the lead after this\nwas accomplished she could force\nMr. Whitehead to sacrifice a trick\neither in spades or clubs. S\nHICKS\nBY HIX\n1 TR,eo\nth,?k hoors\nPASTE?/ an HAIHT.\nWb-\u2014SOT MIHET'\niNYET\nJI 1 V\nEdna Nicholas \u00ab21 Keefer Fl.\nN. W., gets the dollar today. Hicks\nt? r wery or lsi nal\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES /Vahonal Daily WEDNESDAY, MARCH 23, 1927\nSpring Calls Cars\ngF Bl K\nf 'IM\n\u2014Photo by Underwood Underwood\n'ONE OF THE FIRST SIGNS of spring is when father\ncleans, up the old bus for the first Sunday\u2019s trip after\nthe long period of winter idleness- And here is Senator\nArthur Gould of Maine getting his car ready for the\nfirst spring trip.\ndWHATEVER\nI YOU WANT IN A CAR\nI WHATE VE R\nI YOU'RE WILLING TO PAY\ni lit MDoftfiEf Thecarillustnuedis\nthe De Imm Coach\nU w Spare tire eictM\nOiM 1W1E1& OLDSoOBILE\nToday known factors of merit, not And whatever yau\u2019re willing to pay, the\nprice, determine the true value of an more you go over Oldsmobile, point by\nautomobile* point, and study every feature, the more\nWhatever you want in a car, check you realize that here is,indeed,a car at a\nI those known factors in Oldsmobile and moderate price that gratifies your finer\nyouwill find assurance of STANDARD COACH as^es 38 well as satisfies\nsatisfaction the satisfao |M| your every need. Measure\ntion of spirited perform- \u25a0I _ K W any car by these standards\nance, of thrifty operation 1 and good judgment and\nand long life, of comfort, t sound investment sense\nconvenience and distin* will tell you, you must\nguished beauty. consider Oldsmobile.\n100118\nOLDS MOTOR WORKS\nISIS Ulk SL N.Wj WAM.IHGTON branch Phon* Mein 4287\nWuconaia Motor Co. f a, ah w l. 8011. Hav.a Garago\nI C. Kloin A h ff a* AU Fra k S Po, anka 200 South Fairfax St.\n2107 Pa. Avo. N. W. 3700 C-org.* Av.nu. 1120 20th St. N. W. Aloxandria. V./\n,\u2022,J 1\np J\nVisit ths Oldsmobile Exhibit at ths General Motors Permanent Showing, Steel Pier, Atlantic City\nOLD AUTOS GAN\nDE MADE NEW\n\nWhat the well dressed car will\nwear for Easter la all settled, if\nit happens to be a new car. In the\ncase of the older machine, it can be\nsettled easily and to the complete\nsatisfaction of the owper. In. fact,\nnew garb, if the \u2018\u2018tailor\u2019s\u2019\u2019 stock; is\nsuflciehtly large arid his workman\nship known to be good, can make\nthe old car the equal of-any of the\nnew ones that appear in the Easter\nparade.\nThe business of reflnishlng auto\nmobiles has made great strides in\nthe last two years and the bld car\ncan be made to mok as'well as the\nday it came out* ct the salesroom;\naccording ,to Morris Weeks, head of\nthe paint shop of the Washington-\nCaddllac\u2019s Company, maintenance\ndivision. Because many owners jdo\nnot realize this, they drive around\nin shabby looking cars longing for\nthe day when they can afford a new'\none, he says.\nIt makes no difference that the\nbody and tenders are dented. The\ndents can be removd so sucess\nfully that not even a scar remain*;'\nThe upholstery may show signs, of\ngreat wear. It can be replaced\nartistically 'and inexpensively, or\nslip covers can be supplier in ma\nterials more attractive than ever\nbefore.\u2019\nAs to exterior finish, Mr. Weeks\npoints out that the equipment of\nVeteran\ni' v W\nFRANK HAVES, one of the\nveterans of automobtie row. is\nnow with the Washington Cadillac\n\"Company, and this week is in\ncharge of their exhibit at the\nMammoth Used Car Clearance\nSale at the Capital Garage.\nthe large modem paint shop is just'\nas complete and efficient as that\nin the large manufacturing estab\nlishments and capable of applying\nDuco surface just as alluring and\nlasting as that which makes the\n1927 ear a marvel of beauty.\nGOOD AUTO TEAR\nFORECAST\nAn optimistic note on -the spring\nbusiness outlook in the automobile\nindustry, discounting the \u2018saturation\npoint* bugaboo and pointing out\nfavorable conditions throughout the\ncountry, is sounded in a statement\njust issued by Wiliam K. Knudsen,\npresident and general manager of\nthe Chevrolet Motor Company.\n\u201cIn forecasting a continuance of\ngood business prospects for the\nspring months, I am perhaps in\nfluenced by the aspect of our own\nsales which have never been better\nin the history of the company,\u201d said\nKnudsen.\n\u201cAs evidencing steady growth in\nautomobile production during this\nperiod, statistics issued by the\nUnited States Department of Com\nmerce for the last three years cover\ning the six months from January 1\nto June 30 are interesting. The fig\nures for these years follow:\nIn 1924, 2.054,581; 1925, 2,173,525;\n1926, 2,450,780.\nBusiness on Upgrade\n\u201cWith these figures showing busi\nness on the upgrade generally, there\nare only two reasons which could be\nadvanced for a possible decrease In\nsales\u2014first, reaching the so-called\n\u2018saturation point\u2019 \u2014and second, a\ngeneral decline in business produc\ning a reactive tendency in buying.\n\u201cNo one has ever been able to\nadvance any reasonable formula far\nfiguring th* \u2018saturation 'point' Tha\n'two or more* car tend is go pro\nnounced that former theories are\nbeing constantly upset If we kne .v\nthe total area which would be oc\ncupied if- all cars produced were\nrunning within that area, making it\nimposlble for this apace to accommo\ndate any more cars, some basis\nwould bo available tor figuring \u2018satu\nration.** But such a situation is\nimpossible\u2014and we may leave the\n'saturation point* for the future to\ndetermine. Inasmuch as the human\nmind will find It posible to open up\nany bottle-neck of traffic congestion\nwhich might develop.\nProspects Favorable\n\"As for the general trend in busi\nness, country-wide reports show the\nusual spring activity is opening up\n20 days ahead of schedule. With\nthe winter fairly mild, marked only\nby severity in spots, rapid accelera\ntion of municipal and private con\nstruction operations Is indicated.\nFarming should start early, due to\nthe good weather, and manfacturing\noperations generally are in excellent\ncondition.\n\"Rapid turnover at smaller profits\nis the keynote throughout industry\nas reflected by our country** busi\nness. With this policy can only come\na demand for more transportation.\n\"The shippers are demanding bet\nter freight service; the business trav\neler is demanding better train service\nand the automobile user is demand\nihg better service of his car. and the\nfirm that Is in a position to assure\nthe buyer this better service can\nhave nothing but bright prospects\nfor the spring of 1927.\"\n19","height":"30778","width":"24480"}}
